This paper is primarily focused on the performance analysis of TCP over multiple heterogeneous paths in 5G scenarios, which is related to network infrastructure and communication technologies. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). Additionally, the paper also discusses the impact of bandwidth and delay asymmetry on TCP performance, which is related to information theory and communication theory. Hence, cs.IT (Information Theory) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the design of TCP-based CMT solutions for 5G mobile services, which is related to communication systems and protocols, making cs.COMM (Computers and Society) another possible sub-category. The paper also presents a model for performance analysis, which involves mathematical modeling and simulation, making cs.AR (Hardware Architecture) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the impact of path heterogeneity on TCP performance, which is related to computer engineering and hardware design, making cs.CE (Computer Engineering) another possible sub-category.
